        <body>
      
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>N. Y.</placeName> <date>Night after Yom Kippur&#44; 1852</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee>&#58;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Your letter in which you ask me to send you an ethrog im&#45;<lb/>mediately before the holiday&#44; is now before me for answer. I have ful&#45;<lb/>filled your wish&#44; and&#44; on the <date>eve of Yom Kippur</date>&#44; I delivered to the<lb/> express a handsome ethrog&#44; packed in a little box. For it&#44; you will<lb/> please credit my account &#63; The gentleman from <placeName>Nashville</placeName>&#44; about whom<lb/> you wrote to me&#44; did not present himself and therefore&#44; I could not sell him<lb/> a Torah. Will you be good enough to recommend me further <del>in</del> to anyone<lb/> who desires something extraordinary in the way of Torahs. Will you<lb/> please transmit to me three unbound prayer books and one set of<lb/> unbound Pentateuchs. In the hope that the holidays will bring you<lb/> peace and good life&#44; I wish you a happy &#8220;Yom Tov&#8221;&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(5)">Respectfully&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">C. Nussbaum</persName></p>
			<p>As our friend&#44; the proselyte&#44; <persName>Mr. Gretzin</persName>&#44; told me&#44; the report about<lb/> <persName>Marcosson</persName> is not true. He is going to stop several days in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.<lb/> Please be good enough to let me know what you know about these things.<lb/> The obligation really rests upon you&#44; for&#44; &#8220;The mouth that condemned is the<lb/> mouth that should absolve&#8221;.</p>
          <p rend="indent(7)">B</p>
         
        </body>
